abstract: By BERTRAM M. BECK General Director Community Service Society of New York   Social programs designed to help those in need, to give hope and to offer opportunity for the future have been radically reduced during the last two years. The effects, as we at the Community Service Society of New York see them, have been disastrous.   What we have observed in the various service programs we operate throughout the city and what we found in the research we do is a dramatic increase in human misery: growing numbers of homeless people and high unemployment.   And what is even more dramatic is the sense of hopelessness and helplessness among the poor - particularly jobless youth and impoverished aged.   Since 1848 the Community Service Society has been committed to improving the lives of those who are most in need. Today the society is actively pursuing a comprehensive program aimed at improving the lives of those struggling to survive.

abstract: Growing up, I thought that destiny had marked me for a life of impermanence. I wasn't even 2 years old on Nov. 4, 1979, the day my father hoped to get his visa from the American Embassy in Tehran. Having long harbored academic ambitions, my parents had finally decided to emigrate. They were luckier than many Iranians; they had modest savings and letters of acceptance from the University of New Mexico. A U.S. visa was the only thing standing in their way.     Good timing has never been a talent in the Mehran family. That very day, a band of revolutionary students stormed the embassy's front door and took its employees hostage. With the embassy under siege, visas were no longer issued to Iranians, and my parents were forced to abandon their dreams of American academia. Following a friend's advice, they moved to Buenos Aires and opened a Middle Eastern cafe, El Pollo Loco (the Crazy Chicken), where the heady smells of dolmas and spicy beef kebabs were an instant hit with Argentine locals.

lead_paragraph: He was on a 10-day furlough when he first saw the house: a boxy two-story home on Heath Place in woodsy Hastings-on-Hudson, Westchester County. He had been stationed in England when his parents, Charles and Elizabeth Daubek, wrote to say they had saved, scrimped and borrowed to buy it — for $5,000. Now, Pvt. Charles Daubek Jr. stood on the front porch, about to surprise his mother.

abstract: A family comes face to face with  their secret second family.
snippet: A family comes face to face with  their secret second family.
lead_paragraph: I FOLLOWED my father up a crusty staircase in a wholesale meat market in Quito, Ecuador, to watch him sell chicken heads and feet, his latest gig. A onetime millionaire, he looked at me with a wry smile and said, “This is how we pay our bills these days.”

abstract: It’s not only what gets taken away from a family; it’s what each family member gives up.
snippet: It’s not only what gets taken away from a family; it’s what each family member gives up.
lead_paragraph: It was a given that we would be conspicuous. We were four distinctly un-European females  my Midwestern mother; my mentally disabled and legally blind sister; my 14-month-old daughter; and me  going to Brussels and Paris on a pilgrimage of sorts. My sister, Cecily, had long dreamed of visiting the country where she was born and spent her earliest childhood, and also France, for which she’d always felt an affinity because her birthday is Bastille Day.
